{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G4 child-consistency audit — parent 72d5 (Migrate plan-review + completion-verification onto the workflow engine) vs THIS child 92fa (B-UX: Visual editor — select/create criteria, prompts & overlay triggers)]\n\nWalked the 7 cross-child interaction modes against the parent + the whole sibling roster (0408, 101a/B4, 5506/B-DM, 6b06/B2, 723c/B1, 7e48/B6, 961b/B-RETIRE, dc58/B3, f12d/B5). One high-confidence finding; benign readings filtered.\n\nCLEAN modes:\n- Implicit shared state: B-UX edits the v3 batch schema / IR + the prompt library via B-DM's write API; B2/B1 READ packaged library entries. Access is sequenced and non-conflicting (B-UX writes user entries to .rebar/prompts, not the committed reviewers index). CLEAN.\n- Dependency gap (within-roster): B-UX declares its dependency on B-DM (5506 blocks 92fa) and the v3 batch schema; the producer exists and left a hand-off. No missing producer/consumer link. CLEAN.\n- Ordering violation: B-DM lands before B-UX, matching B-UX's stated dependency. CLEAN.\n- Consumer impact: B-UX is the sole consumer of B-DM's enumerate/create API; contract satisfied. No downstream sibling consumes B-UX output. CLEAN.\n- Residual references: no sibling deletes/renames a symbol B-UX relies on; B6 removes only examples/code_review.yaml + templates.py, untouched by B-UX's editor_assets/server work. CLEAN.\n\nFINDING (mode: conflicting assumptions / scope overlap with the PARENT)\n- finding: B-UX is structurally inconsistent with the parent epic's stated scope and its migration siblings. The parent's What / Out-of-scope / Success / Acceptance criteria are exclusively about (a) migrating plan-review onto the engine, (b) migrating completion-verification, (c) planned-trace parity, (d) cutover with signing intact, (e) removing throwaway samples — every one a READ/WIRE/CUTOVER/DELETE operation over the EXISTING substrate. The parent's ONLY visual-editing mention is RETENTION of epic A's demo workflow \"as the unused visual-editing refinement sample\" (What + AC5) — a sample to refine AGAINST, not an editor feature to BUILD. B-UX instead builds net-new editor authoring (library-backed dropdowns, inline overlay-trigger creation, full in-editor criterion/prompt authoring, an editor-server endpoint, Playwright E2E) whose justification roots in epic A's editor and the B-DM write path, not in any parent migration/parity/cleanup criterion. So B-UX (with its backing data-model sibling B-DM/5506) sits under this migration epic without an anchoring parent acceptance/success criterion, and its core assumption (the editor must gain select/create authoring over the library) is not shared by the parent or any migration sibling.\n- criteria: [parent What, parent Out of scope, parent Success Criteria, parent AC1, parent AC2, parent AC3, parent AC4, parent AC5, parent AC6]\n- location: child 92fa Why/What/Scope/Acceptance (all five ACs); parent 72d5 What / Out of scope / Success Criteria / Acceptance Criteria\n- evidence: [\"Parent SC: 'plan-review and completion-verification run on the ONE workflow-engine substrate ... validated by offline planned-trace parity ...; only real workflows remain (samples removed)' — no editor/authoring deliverable\", \"Parent What enumerates 4 bullets (migrate plan-review, migrate completion-verifier, planned-trace parity, remove sample stubs) + 'KEEP epic A's demo workflow as the unused visual-editing refinement sample' — the sole visual-editing mention is RETENTION of a sample, not authoring of an editor\", \"Parent AC5 references the editor only as the retained 'visual-editing refinement sample'; no parent AC names dropdowns, in-editor authoring, an editor-server endpoint, or Playwright E2E\", \"Child 92fa ACs are entirely about visual-editor select/create authoring (library-backed dropdowns, inline trigger creation, in-editor criterion/prompt authoring via the B-DM API, real-browser E2E) — none maps to any parent AC\", \"Child 92fa Why roots its justification in epic A's editor + the B2 migration making the batch criteria list the primary edited thing — an editor-UX concern, not a parent migration/parity/cleanup criterion\", \"Whole-roster cross-check: every parent AC is covered by a migration sibling — AC1->B2(6b06)/B1(723c); AC2->B3(dc58); AC3->B4(101a); AC4->f12d(f12d)+0408; AC5/AC6->B6(7e48). The migration/parity/cleanup set is complete WITHOUT B-UX, so B-UX (and B-DM) are additive beyond the epic's bounded deliverables.\", \"Sibling 5506 (B-DM) already carries the symmetric G4 finding for the same editor lineage and names this child: 'mirrors the G3 structural finding already logged on sibling 92fa (B-UX)'. B-UX is the front-end half of the same un-anchored lineage.\"]\n- scenarios: [\"Epic 72d5 reaches its AC6 end-state (two real workflows + one sample, lint+suite green) via B1/B2/B3/B4/B5/B6 while B-UX/B-DM are still open -> the epic's AC/SC are fully satisfiable yet two children remain, so 'epic done' is ambiguous and the acceptance set does not bound the actual deliverables.\", \"An implementer/reviewer tracing parent criteria -> children finds B-UX with no parent anchor and cannot tell whether the epic's migration/cleanup goal depends on the visual-editor authoring work or is independent of it.\", \"B-UX wires the editor to write the prompt library; with B-DM's create/update plus the pre-existing prompt_authoring.save_prompt path noted in B-UX's own review, two write paths to the drift-gated library now exist in this lineage with no parent criterion governing which is canonical.\"]\n- impact: Scope-broadening / traceability gap. A child carries net-new effort (a selection/authoring front-end, an editor-server write endpoint, Playwright E2E, library-backed picker wiring) that no parent acceptance/success criterion accounts for; the parent treats the visual editor only as a retained sample, not a deliverable. The epic can be 'done' per AC1-AC6 while B-UX/B-DM are open (or vice-versa). No parent criterion is left UNCOVERED (the migration/parity/cleanup set is fully covered by siblings), so this is a child-without-parent-anchor / scope-misalignment consistency finding, not a coverage gap.\n- checklist_item: Check the 7 cross-child modes (implicit shared state, conflicting assumptions, dependency gap, scope overlap, ordering violation, consumer impact, residual references) — each detected mode is a finding.\n- suggested_fix: Either (a) add a parent acceptance criterion making the visual-editor select/create authoring (and its B-DM data-model backing) an explicit epic deliverable — e.g. \"the visual editor lets a human SELECT/CREATE the migrated plan-review batch's criteria, prompts, and overlay triggers from the library (drift-gate-green)\" — tying B-UX + B-DM to the epic's intent and stating whether AC6 'done' is gated on them; or (b) if the editor-authoring work is a separate concern (it builds on epic A's editor, not the migration), re-parent B-UX (92fa) + B-DM (5506) out of this epic so 72d5's children are exactly the migration/parity/cleanup stories its ACs enumerate. If (a) is chosen, also note the canonical library write path (B-DM create/update vs the pre-existing prompt_authoring.save_prompt) so the lineage does not keep two drift-gate write paths.\n\nNote: this mirrors the G4 finding already logged on sibling 5506 (B-DM); B-UX is the front-end half of the same un-anchored editor lineage, so resolving one (re-parent or add-parent-AC) should resolve both."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782509143758636001,"uuid":"4968cf9e-4d74-435e-9fcb-70e684019566"}